    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Seat Belts, Speeding And the Governor</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lillian Swickle, Bruce S Rosen and William Stephenson letters on Jamie Lincoln Kitman's April 22 Op-Ed article on New Jersey Gov Jon Corzine's automobile accident</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Corzine's Wild Ride,'' by Jamie Lincoln Kitman (Op-Ed, April 22):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Corzine's Wild Ride,'' by Jamie Lincoln Kitman (Op-Ed, April 22):</p>
        <p>Although I support and voted for Gov. Jon Corzine, I am concerned that he chose to disobey the seat belt law and the state troopers were powerless to enforce it.</p>
        <p>Lillian Swickle  Bridgewater</p>
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Over the weekend my 9-year-old son, Jacob, noticed that I hadn't put my seatbelt on as we started backing out of the driveway (I always buckle up except sometimes for driving to the supermarket around the corner). ''Corzine, Dad, Corzine,'' he said.</p>
        <p>That's all he had to say.</p>
        <p>Bruce S. Rosen  Bernardsville</p>
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Jamie Lincoln Kitman properly states that all right-thinking people extend their hearts and best wishes to Gov. Jon Corzine.</p>
        <p>The seat belt issue has received sufficient attention. The thing that has received no attention is the callous disregard for the lives of the law-abiding citizens who were simply trying to get out of the way of this huge S.U.V., hurtling down the Garden State Parkway at an unconscionable speed.</p>
        <p>The lives of these citizens were deliberately jeopardized -- for nothing.</p>
        <p>William Stephenson  Princeton</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
